summary: Arya’s whole arc throughout the past several seasons has been about her struggle to deal with the pain that comes with her...
body:
Why both Arya and Gendry will survive the battle of Winterfell (theory)

Arya’s whole arc throughout the past several seasons has been about her struggle to deal with the pain that comes with her identity and being who she is, which is why she ever decided to become faceless in the first place. That whole emotionless, unfeeling, lethal murderess was her attempting to get away from her identity. That wasn’t her. She’s fiesty, she’s hot headed, she’s smart, she’s loyal, she’s loving, and most of all, she’s EXTREMELY emotional! The Arya we saw from seasons 1-3 was the real Arya. Seasons 4-6 was her distancing herself from all that made her herself. Arya has the wolf’s blood, she gets very passionate about things that impact her in a more aggressive way. She also very clearly has deeply intense feelings for Gendry, and she’s dealing with that by attempting to go back to that detached faceless person who is in complete control of everything, but she’s finding that she’s unable to. This is pretty well evidenced by when he slammed the axe into the block of wood and watching her reaction. You could see that she was impressed, and you can see the moment when she caught herself and slipped that mask back on (gif below).

I honestly think that she and Gendry are kind of a package deal at this point. Him being there is reminding her of the last time she was her true self, when she was with him. After he was taken, she witnessed the Red fucking Wedding, which really fucked her up, and that’s when I believe she made the decision to distance herself from her emotions to numb the pain. There’s an example in the first person she killed that wasn’t out of self defense. You could sense the vengeance in her, the more aggressive wolf’s blood impulses twisting into violence after experiencing such traumatic events. When she reunited with Jon, she seemed to slip back into that true identity, that sharp tongued, happy, emotional person that she was before. When she reunited with Gendry, it seemed to really force the mask off in an almost painful way. The last time she had seen him, she had lost every member of her family (not necessarily to death, but also to circumstance and situation), and it was around that time that the pain got too difficult to bear, making way for the faceless mask to take over. You can see her mask slipping, and you can see her readjusting several times. Gendry’s death would just be a catalyst into her slipping back into that faceless and numb version of herself for good, which would just destroy everything that her arc has sought to accomplish. Her whole story is about accepting that pain is a part of life and there’s no true escape from it. And if Gendry lives, she really can’t run away from those emotions, she’ll be forced to look at it head on. It’ll be impossible for her to put the mask back on, which is kinda the whole point. It would be pointless and senseless to end her story with no satisfactory or meaningful conclusion. What would that say? That to be emotional is to be weak? I think we all know better than that. Every death has meaning. Her and Gendry’s deaths would leave both of those characters’ entire storylines void of meaning and moral, which is the opposite of what this series is about.

Anyways, thank you for coming to my ted talk.

summary: I know episode 3 is going to be all death and destruction... but I just want one moment of levity at the beginning where...
body:
I know episode 3 is going to be all death and destruction… but I just want one moment of levity at the beginning where everyone is gathering to fight, except no one can find Arya, and Bran says she’s in the grain room, so Sansa and/or Jon go to fetch her and find her asleep curled up next to Gendry, and they’re just flabbergasted!  

Well, I’m torn between that, and wanting no one to know until after the battle, when they’ve both survived, but have gotten separated. So when they see each other, they run into each others arms with everyone looking on like, “what?” and Bran’s just, “yeah, that’s a thing now!”
